ding $ak. Is conducted to a cottage, and lies in a barn. &sect; <HI>XXIX.</HI> Un|dergoes &s;urpri&s;ing hard&s;hips. &sect; <HI>XXX.</HI> Is cordially received by Mr. Lane of Stafford&s;hire; and rides before that gentleman's daughter to the neighbourhood of Bri&s;tol. &sect; <HI>XXXI.</HI> Finds a &s;afe retreat in the hou&s;e of colonel Francis Wyndham. Is in imminent danger of being di&s;covered near Lyme in Dor&s;et&s;hire. &sect; <HI>XXXII.</HI> Embarks at Brig$t$elm&s;tead, and lands in Normandy. &sect; <HI>XXXIII.</HI> The earl of Derby is beheaded. &sect; <HI>XXIV.</HI> Scotland is incorporated with England. &sect; <HI>XXXV.</HI> Prince R$p$rt $$i$s to the We&s;t-Indies; and Ireland is totally reduced. &sect; <HI>XXXVI.</HI> Moti$es for a war with the Dutch. &sect; <HI>XXXVII.</HI> The States-General &s;end amba&s;&s;adors to London. &sect; <HI>XXXVIII.</HI> Sea-engagement in the Downs between ad|miral B$ake and V$n Tr$mp. &sect; <HI>XXXIX.</HI> Declaration of war between the two republics. &sect; <HI>XL.</HI> A drawn battle off Plymouth between Sir George Ay&s;$ue and De Ruyter. &sect; <HI>XLI.</HI> Blake is wor&s;ted at the back of the Goodwin Sands by Van Tromp and De Ruyter. &sect; <HI>XLII.</HI> The&s;e are defeated, after a de&s;perate engage|ment with the Engli&s;h fleet, commanded by Monk and Deane. &sect; <HI>XLIII.</HI> Crom|well re&s;olves to make him&s;elf ab&s;olute. &sect; <HI>XLIV.</HI> He di&s;&s;olves the parliament by force. &sect; <HI>XLV.</HI> Account of Oliver. &sect; <HI>XLVI.</HI> Aims of different parties. &sect; <HI>XLVII.</HI> He con$$kes the Barebone parliament. &sect; <HI>XLVIII.</HI> A &s;ea-engage|ment off the coa&s;t of Flanders, in which the Engli&s;h have the advantage. &sect; <HI>XLIX.</HI> Another more desperate off the Texel, in which Van Tromp is &s;lain, and the Dutch f$eet defeated. &sect; <HI>L.</HI> Negotiation with the Dutch. &sect; <HI>LI.</HI> The parliament &s;ur|re$$er their power to Cromwell. &sect; <HI>LII.</HI> Who is cho&s;en protector.</P>
